 From whence came American Cool? These are the questions Peter Stearns seeks to answer in this timely and engaging volume. American Cool focuses extensively on the transition decades, from the erosion of Victorianism in the 1920s to the solidification of a cool culture in the 1960s. Beyond describing the characteristics of the new directions and how they altered or amended earlier standards, the book seeks to explain why the change occurred. It then assesses some of the outcomes and longer-range consequences of this transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMiddle classzUnited StatesxPsychology. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814771037.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814771037zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814771037/original  a978-3-11-071692-4 New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA